<DOC><DOCNO> AP890425-0023 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0242EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-China-Looters     04-25 0237</FIRST><SECOND>PM-China-Looters,0242</SECOND><HEAD>Police Arrest 98 In Changsha Rioting</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police in the southern city of Changsha arrested98 people, just six of them students, for looting that occurredduring a student demonstration last weekend, an official newspaperreported today.   The People's Daily said those arrested were caught looting 28shops and a shopping arcade Saturday in what the official pressdescribed as the worst rioting in 40 years of Communist rule.   Rioting also broke out Saturday in the ancient capital of Xian,with crowds throwing rocks and setting fire to buildings andvehicles.   The daily said that of the 98 detained in Changsha, 32 wereworkers, 28 were unemployed, 26 were peasants, six wereself-employed and six were students. It said 52 were waiting trial.   The outbreaks of violence occurred as university students inBeijing and other cities took to the streets to mourn formerCommunist Party chief Hu Yaobang, a reformist who died April 15,and call for democratic reforms.   In Beijing on Saturday, 150,000 students congregated onTiananmen Square in the center of the city for a peacefuldemonstration. Student leaders in Beijing have made efforts to keepunemployed youth and other potential troublemakers out of theirranks.   Most of the other demonstrations have also been peaceful,although foreign sources said students at the Agricultural Collegein Hefei, eastern China, last week smashed windows and furniture ina campus cafeteria.</TEXT></DOC>